<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-10T02:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-10T02:00:00-05:00" n="378" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d378">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/7–1044: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-10T14:00:00+07:00">July 10,
                                1944—2 p.m.</date>
                            <lb/> [Received July 10—9:53 a.m.]</dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1189. Press correspondents have reportedly returned from their visit to Yenan
                        and are en route to Chungking. We have not as yet received from the United
                        States any copies of the press despatches or articles written by them, and
                        accordingly do not know whether it has been possible for them to make
                        comprehensive factual reports.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>